review_blob: Very average IPA.  Has the aroma, flavor, and stength of any IPA but lacks and distinguishing characteristics
Very little head with syrupy pour.  Nice nose with decent taste.  Not the best oatmeal stout but a good tasting beer for getting it for free.
beer_name: Stoudts Fat Dog Stout (Vintages 2004 and later)

review_blob: On tap at the Brickskellar.  Didnt actually order it but tried some of BuckNakeds.  Decent sour aroma.  Very tart to the lips with a watery head that fizzles away.  Cherry tartness, with citrus flavors.  Dently drinkable.

Draft in Bar None in the Citaaay.  I was very thirsty when I drank this so it added to the enjoyment.  Despite its quenching capabilities, this pilsner is nothing to brag about.  The lager is much better than this mundane brew.  Some hoopiness combined with malts that makes a slightly abover average pilsner.  Definitely overrated on this site.

Year old bottle that I slowly let warm after openning.  Aroma of slowly backing bread with jellys and jams of the farm.  Appears medium thick with suspended carbonation.  Meduim sweet flavor with a bitter turning to ever so slightly bitter finish.  Palate has a full body with slight carbonation and a long slightly oily finish.  Overall this is a great belgian style which masks the alcohol content well.  Very flavorful and another victory for Victory.

Hearty aroma with hints of caramel, coffee, hazel nut, pecan, and other various forrest nuts and brush.  All the forrest flavors are complimented by the overtones of chocolate flavor.  Pours thick and black with cloudy and medium tan head.  Very sweet with smooth chocolate taste that belnds well with the other subtle flavors.  Full creamy body with long finish.  This is a damn good imperial!

Bitter hoppy aroma with hints of bitter spruce and herbs.  Pours amber brown with a slight haze and minimal head.  Medium bitter flavor that is neither overwhelming or distinct.  However there is a slight carmel sweetness that gives the beer something extra.  Lively carbonation with a medium body that finishes medium to long with bitter hints that linger on the tongue.  I solid German Alt.

Aroma of caramel, nuts, and raosted garlic.  Pours thick and syrupy with a maple syrup like reminder.  The flavor is thick with hints of leaves and basement flavors such as rusty axe and yeasty barrel.   Full body with oil feel but smooth finish.  This beer is great and I recommmend this to anyone who likes Barely wine and seasonal specials.

Wow, havent rated a beer in quite some time.  So I thought I would treat myself to a decent beer from dogfish head.  The ulmighty pangaea.  However, this beer isnt as good as I remember.  There is a week aroma of barnyard cheese and basement flavors.  This malted beverage has a hazy rose colored hue.  There is a slight sweet to sour flavor that hits ther tongue throughout the drink.  Their is a medium to light body with slight carbonation and medium particle content.  I dont know what dog fish head did but the spices from all the continents didnt mesh together well at all...no wonder they continents split up.  They are better a part! Dont mess with history DFH.

Bottle of 2004 courtesy of Kevbert.  Aroma of hoppps and wheaty fruit goodness.  Cant commment on the Pour because I drank it from the bottle but from the picture its seems pretty average.  When  i took the first drink I got taken back by a barrage of flavors.  However the boys at Petes need to pick some flavors that actually mesh well together.  I detected alot of that caramel/molasses/sweet beet flavor that is the sign of a garbage beer.  This is still above average but definitely nothing to brag about!

Im pissed off because I  just lost my first game of beirut to Kevbert.   However drinking this beer is my only saving grace.  Though Ive had this beer several times, Ive appreciated its rich aroma and slight bitter hoppy excelence until now.  Great alluring aroma that tempts you drink even more.  Pours amber with an aroma of bitter hoppimess.  This is what an IPA should taste like!  Besides the ton o hops, there are hints of grass, hay, wheat, rice, corn  tomoatoes, and summer squash.  Soooo good this beer!

Bottle in Wilder.  Aroma of skunky yeast and sour mash.  Cant describe the pour because Im not dignifying this beer with a glass.  Bland taste with hints of skunk and  wet horse blanket.  Not very good...I dont care where this beer is imported from...probably my ass.

Bottle at On the Rocks.  Nice yeasty aroma with a fine amber pour that was suprising for a lager.  The taste was also impressive with hints of honey, oats, and hay.  Nice smooth mouthfeel and medium body.  Needs a slight addition of malts but overall this was a great choice for the price.

Pretty inspried by Bucknakeds rating of this saison.  The aroma is a of a floral English garden with hints of tulip, rose, and orchid.  The flavor is definitely alot like green garden hose and rusty shovel.  But seriously this beer is definitely a spring saison with undertones of grapes, herbs, spices, and champagne.     Finished alittle chalky but i think it might be the glass or on my tongue.  Sour overtones of tart apples, peaches, and more green garden hose.  Decent beer overall.

Enjoying 2004 bottle that was 98 cents at beers of the world with kevin rezai..he doesnt have a rate beer name so we will refer to him as Kevbert.  Wow the first thing I realize is that this beer really isnt that bad.  No aroma, but the flavor is decently smooth with slight honey and yeast flavors.  I cant really say that this is jewel of Indian Beer but not too bad.  Just realized that this beer has alittle chalkiness to it at the finish..alittle put off by this but oh well.  Sorry Bucknaked but I will split another one with you.

Bottle at Alexander Street Pub.  Didnt see how it pours because i drank it from the bottle.  Aroma of glass and corn.  Flavor of more of the same.  Taste have hints of slights hops, rice, grain, and yeast.  Easy to drink and definitely got drunk off this beer.  Not the King of Beers!

On tap at the Mex.  Pours amber brown with medium hops and head.  Aroma of candy and caramel.  Flavor is very malty with hints of Life Savers and other candy flavors.  Butter Scotch is overwehleming in the nose and finish of this beer.  However this is a very refreshing change from the shitty mexican beer that I have been drinking all night.  I would definitely drink this malty flavorful beer again.  Rohrbach has never impressed me but this beer on tap shows some serious prospects.

In bottle during the "beer game" at Simon.  Aroma of glass and metal.  Non offensive aroma with hints of rice and grain.  Canadian flavors of purified water and moose antlers with rice and corn.  Better than the original Blue and easy drinking.  Watchout of heavy drinking with this beer because the next day your ass will pay.

Draught at the MEX.  Pours dark brown with a lime.  The aroma is of lime and citus fruit.  This is because there is a lime in the pint.  However the taste is of mexican wheat and rice.  The taste is decent and flavorful.  However any beer that need a lime to make it taste better is in need of serious refinement.  One of my favorite mexican brews.

Draught at the Elmwood.  Pours golden brown with medium carbonation and frothy head.  Not much aroma or flavor.  The taste has subtle sweetness and hops but definitely lacking in flavor.  This beer is no good.

Bottle of some random year.  Every year seems to bad when this "beer" is bottled.  The appearance is amazing with a pale yellow that seems to fade as it warms.  Pours kinds like giner ale but with no flavor or aroma at all.  Cant finish this beer but definitly didnt expect to.  But hey look at how many carbs I just cut!..WOW AMAZING 100th beer!  Heres to you boys!

On tap at the Elmwood.  Pours beaming Yellow with high carbonation.  Aroma of yeast and wheat.  Taste is more yeast and wheat combined with alittle grain and rice flavoring.  Pretty dry overall with slight hoppy flavoring.  Very water and thin.  Drank this beer in Verona and I remember it being much better then.

On tap at the Elmwood.  Pours Amber Brown with aroma of tart apples and peaches.  The sweetness of this beer overwhelms any other flavors attempting to escape to the mouth.  The overall taste and mouthfeel are of water with slight beer sweetness.  No malt or hops present at all.  Wasnt very impressed at all.

On tap at the Elmwood after finishing midterms.  Pours a nice Golden Brown with a frothy head.  Nice hoppy aroma with some wheat and barley undertones.  Taste is mildly hoppy with a nice crisp flavor that lingers on the tongue.  Great easy drinking beer that started the style according to ClarkVV.

2004 bottle.  Pours with high carbonation and an amber brown, light body look.  Aroma of tart apples and peaches.  Taste is light with slight malty flavors of citrus.  Very smooth and quenching with a crisp finish.  Very carbonated with lots of head and small particles in suspension.  Good triple that had no flavor of alcohol.  Nicely balanced nose and finish.  Good ale.

Wow so much to tell, so much to tell.  Just smoked a cigarette for no reason in below freezing temps.  Went out on the balcony at 2am after studying for operations midterm.  Had to removes some snow with a spoon just to get the door open.  The cigaraettes I have were left in my car by a homeless man after he stole the quarters i kept in there for tolls and such.  This double bock is amazing with an aroma of malty molasses and toffee.  Very strong flavor with hints of chocolate and caramel.  Very sweet flavors that me in my drunken state cannot identify after the smoke and doritos im currently eating.  However I know this is a good beer because it warms my chest as i feel like im about to pass out.  YAY

2004 bottle.  Pours a beautiful opaque pale orange with head the fizzes quickly to the top of the tulip.  Very high carbonation with a delicate mouthfeel.  Aroma of citrus and apple sause that tickles the nose.  Unfortunately the flavor is not giving me what i was expecting.  The sublte farmhouse spices seem to be watered-down and are not pronounced on the tongue.  Very little aftertaste as well.  However it is very crisp, smooth and well-balanced.  Yeast is present, but not overwhelming which is a plus in my book.  Second decent beer from this brewery.  However both have been alittle overrated in my opinion.

2004 Bottle.  Pours balck somewhat like old engine oil.  I would say old becuase its darker than the new synthetic engine oils these youngsters use in their hip new rides.  Actually is does pour like old engine oil.  Aroma of Vanilla and Chocolate.  One must defintiely like vanilla and chocolate flavors in beer to appreciate this after-dinner brew.  Do wish the mouth feel was alittle thicker since it is called old engine oil.  Mouthfeel is more like new engine oil.  Fullbody is more like old engine oil than new engine oil.  Nice bittery finish combined with roasted malts that reminds me of old engine oil.

2004 Bottle.  Pours a smooth dark amber with more carbonation that expected from an Barley Wine.  The aroma is very citrus with hints of toffee and barley of course.  The taste is weaker and less malty than most Barely Wines.  However, it has unique style that makes this well balanced brew a pleasure to drink.  Its light and flavorful with a slightly bitter finish.  Hides the alcohol well and is definitely worth a try.

Bottle 2004.  Pours dark with a moderately light head that disperses quickly w/ medium carbonation.  Strong aroma of chocolate malts and pine needles.  Taste is well balanced with a malty sweet nose and a slightly bitter finish.  Very mellow porter that is very easy and enjoyable to drink.  More roasted malts and hops could replace some of the water in this porter to fortify its flavor.  Other than that this is definitely a classic American porter that is great all year long.

Bottle 2004.  Pours a light amber with carbonated head that slowly disperses leaving a nice lacing on the sides of the glass.  The aroma is very malty with a piney aromatic fragrance that lingers in the air.  The taste is quite wonderful with bitter hoppiness combined with a well balanced spicey flavor.  The bottle claims that some might think this beer is over hopped but i think it is just right.  Very smooth and crisp which makes drinking the 1 and a half pint bottle seem like nothing.  Expensive but worth it for an IPA lover like myself.

2004 bottle.  Pours brownish amber with decent head that disperses quickly with white foam that laces the glass.  Aroma is fruity and spicey with a tempting alure.  Taste is alittle disappointing with the major taste being of watery hops.  I do like the lightness and drinkablity of the beer.  Seems to be a overload of flour and wheat present in the flavor.  Still a decent drinking beer and is crisp and fresh.  This beer would go well before dinner as an apertif.

$2 bottles at Nathaniels.  Pours brownish golden with aroma of glass and water.  Lots of flavor but mostly of watered down dirty hops and barley.  Has a very strong taste with a bittery finish that lingers on the tongue.  This taste is like a red flag to stop drinking this beer before you go blind.

Bottled and On tap.  This a classic American Lager.  Many run of the mill beer drinkers view this beer as a delicasy, while Ive never see its appeal.  Pours pale brown with a watery presence.  The aroma and flavor are above average.  Despite the mass producing the hoppy bitterness lingers well on the palate while subtle flavors of rice, wheat, and tea leaf are present.  Much better on tap but still not something I order regularly despite its crisp finish.

Bottled, canned, and on tap all the time in western New York.  Pours golden-yellow with dry herb and barley taste.  Alittle bit more drinkable than Blue Light.  Is the beer of choice in many area bars.  Low on taste and aroma while somehow maintaining the illusion of a good beer.  Possibly because it will get you drunk just as good as the next beer.

2005 on tap at Cali Rollin Sushi Bar.  Pours golden with medium carbonation.  Aroma of barley and eastern spices.  Goes amazing with great sushi as ClarkVV and Bucknaked both pointed out.  Wasbi undertones are subtle with soy rounding out the circle of flavors.  I would drink this beer without sushi but the entire sushi experience at the restaurant is what makes this brew so special.  Also good for saki bombs while singing Tiny Dancer.

2004 bottle: Pours thin with dark color and small head that disappears quickly.  Aroma is pretty amazing with hints of coffee, mocha, chocolate, butterscotch, and caramel.  However the mouthfeel kills the mood.  I cant stand thin porters.  Porters need to have alittle meat on their bones and alittle thickness to their mouthfeel.  The flavors are their but the water that is added to this beer needs to cut in half.  American porters need to take some notes from the Brits when it comes to this style of beer.

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: 2004 bottle.  Pours a thin brown with meduim head.  Slight aroma of hops and yeast.  Flavor is very weak for an IPA.  Hops are detectible but the additional spices and barley dont compliment the brew well.  Way too watery which kills and IPA flavor that exists.  Easy too drink and unoffensive however.

Water Street Music Hall 2004 bottle.  Pours medium brown with watery carbonation.  The aroma is of sugar added genessee river water.  Taste and appearance are neither of honey nor brown.  Alittle bit of false advertising.  You know its bad when the bartender gives a weird look when you ask for one at an open bar.

Bottle at Thali of India 2005.  Asked for Kingkfisher but got this beer instead.  Pours golden-yellow with watery appearance.  Aroma is of slight hops and barley.  Tastes of watery corn and indian wheat and soybeans.  Went decent with the dinner but this beer is definitely not made for the connisour.  India definitely not known for their beers.

Bottle 2004.  Pours thin and brown with high carbonation.  Aroma with hints of sour fruit and spices.  The taste reminds me of spiced fruits and tart sweet yams.  The mouth feel reminds me of a sparkling italian wine with medium particles in suspension.  This a unique and flavorful abbey that finishes just as spicey as it begins.

Guest Draft at the Old Toad.  Alittle hesitant to try this sour ale but the risk payed off.  The aroma was of sour apples and cherries.  I was prepared for a very sour taste but when i took my first sip I was pleasantly surprised.  The sour beginning was overtaken by the sweet finish.  The flavors were all over the board but all good.  The high carbonation of this sour ale brings out the flavors in every sip of this exquist style of ales.

On tap at the Old Toad.  Pours Dark brown with a nice lacely head that sat on top with a graceful glow.  Very nice falvorful aroma.  Flavorful taste for an organic with roasted chocolate, butterscotch, vanilla, caramel malts.  Very enjoyable experience and made me appreciate the organic nature of this brew.  Damn good brewery.

Guest Draft at the Old Toad.  Pours very thin for a barley wine.  First of this lighter style that Ive tried.  Smells almost like a Flemish Sour Ale but is definitely a barley wine.  Pours pale amber with higher than usual carbonation.  Tastes bitterly sweet with alittle watery mouthfeel.  This was an exotic treat that seems to be getting a bad rap from this sight.  Once you get passed the original awkwardness of the style, youll appreciate the subtle apple and cherry undetones.

2005 "Real Ale" on cask at the Old Toad.  Pours Black with chocolate ring of foam.  Aroma of chocolate and caramel roasted malts with hints of herbs and spices of the vast fields of honeoye falls ny.  However the mouth feel and taste are quite dissappointing.  Very watery with mild flavors that are very weak.  I remember this beer being much better than this.  However, my taste buds dont lie.
beer_name: Custom Brewcrafters Double Dark Cream Porter

review_blob: 2005 bottle.  Pours thick and gritty with syrupy presence that is a think and amber brown colored.  Aroma alittle strong with hints of malty oats and squash.  Taste has hints of black licorice and caramel molasses.  Looking at the wine through the light I can see large particles in suspension and it just makes this brew so much more appealing.  The flavor is very above average and am pleasantly surprised with this brewery.  DFefinitely gonna try a few more from here.
beer_name: Flying Dog Horn Dog Barley Wine

review_blob: 2005 Bottle.  Aroma of chocolate and coffee with hints of vanilla and oaky bitterness.  Smooth beginning with a nice flavors roasted caramel malts and coffee undertones.  This slightly sweet smoothness is complimented with a bitter-hoppy finish.  Definiterly still tasting vanilla.  The base is alittle watery for my liking...would be amazing if it was unfiltered.

Pours a surprising amber color that seems promising with a slight fizzy head.  The first taste is alittle boring with english hops and barley and slight flavors amaretto and apricots.  However, the beer leaves the mouth quite dry and the bitterness of the hops isnt well balanced by the sweetness of the malts.  Alittle let down by this beer

2005 at the Cambridge Brew Pub.  Enjoyed from a 3 liter portable tap at the bar with good friends.  Slight aroma of yeast and hops with a nice smooth pour of golden sunshine.  Flavor is mild and enjoyable with subtle spicy flavors and slight hops and barley.  So fresh and clean, a great beer to end the night with.

Enjoyed with wild curry (3 star) at the King and I restaurant 2005.  Very faint aroma of yeast and hops and pour golden with high carbonation.  Yeasty taste that comes off stronger than American beers.  Not the best of brews but complimented the meal nicely.
